<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Inquiry on Disability and International Development - Written Evidence from Leonard Cheshire Disability to the House of Commons Select Committee on International Development</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:right"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Inquiry on Disability and International Development - Written Evidence from Leonard Cheshire Disability to the House of Commons Select Committee on International Development</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Leonard Cheshire Disability believes that disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">be at the heart of development. Disability must therefore be explicitly referenced in the post-2015 development framework.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> With </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approximately</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a billion disabled people across the globe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it will simply not be possible to secure the optimum development outco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mes unless disabled people are fully included and mainstreamed within </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development programmes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To this end we believe that the UK Government must be at the forefront of pushing for disability to be referenced in the post-2015 development framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> UK is well placed to be a leading voice in this call, which could help ensure that millions of disabled people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are fully included in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recognise that there has been a willingness to pursue this agenda within the Department for Internat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ional Development, particularly through a number of key programmes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would however suggest that it is difficult to identify the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> extent to which mainstreaming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of disability issues has actually </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">happened across the Department. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">suggest that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Department produce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> a specific disability strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with a set of clear outcomes and indic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ators to measure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> its impact on disabled people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We recommend that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">a full-time senior civil servant is appointed in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> to oversee the implementation of this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> strategy.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recommend that the Department </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> a monitoring and evaluation framework that specifically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">measures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">inclusion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">in their mainstream policies and programmes, at both global and country levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recommend that DFID looks to fu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">institutional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and capacity building </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of disabled people’s organisations in low and middle income countries.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recommend that explicit reference is made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the inclusion of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disabled people and their allies in future DFID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">funded disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-specific and mainstream</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> initiatives.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is clear from our research that there is no “one size fits all” solution to addressing the entrenched and systematic exclusion and poverty of disabled people in developing countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">therefore recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> that DFI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">D takes a key strategic role in negotiating with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">fellow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">bilateral a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nd multilateral donor agencies to develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> appropriate tools for moni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">toring the impact of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> disability-specific </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and mainstream development programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Leonard Cheshire Disability</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">At Leonard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Cheshire Disability, we work for a society in which every person is equally valued. We believe that disabled people should have the freedom to live their lives the way they choose - with the opportunity and support to live independently, to contribute econ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">omically, and to participate fully in society.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eonard Cheshire Disability's International Department works through five regional </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offices in Africa and Asia. We support</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> children with disabilities to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">get an education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, adults with disabilities to earn a living, and all disabled people to access the rehabilitation, health and other support they need. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also campaign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to put disability at the heart of international development, and support young disabled peop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le to campai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gn for their rights through our Young Voices p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rogramme</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition, the Leonard Cheshire Disability and Inclusive Development Centre, University College London (which is part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> International Department), undertakes world-class qualitative and quant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">itative research in the field of disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and international development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We focus on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policy analysis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, disability and poverty, livelihoods, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inclusive education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disability in conflict-affected countries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and in disaster and emergency situations</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Evid</span><span style="color:#365f91; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ence submission</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The adequacy of DFID’s current policy commitments on disability and development, and whether it needs a disability strategy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leonard Cheshire Disability recognises and welcomes the leading role that DFID has taken in the field on disabilit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y and international development during the past 15 years. This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidenced by the production of the issues paper, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Disability, Poverty and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, (2000), which spearheaded the highly influential “twin track approach” to disability programming. DFID has also been proactive in commissioning four discrete research programmes on disability and international development issues, which has made a signifi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cant contribution to the growing body of knowledge in this field, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence that is now regularly used to support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the UN </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Convention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on Rights of Persons with Disabilities (UNCRPD).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID has also produced a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How to Note on Working on Disability in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Country Programmes,</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">written primarily for DFID country staff. However, since its publication in 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">009, there is little evidence of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the extent to which this has influenced DFID’s programmes and policies at country level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the recent past, there has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> increasing commitment by DFID to incorporate and mainstream disability issues within its core programmes. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> International Development, Lynne Featherstone, has a personal commitment to disability issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This is to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commended. However, it is important that this personal commitment becomes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">institutionalised within DFID, so that disability continues to be prioritise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> international development, both within the UK Government, and also by other leading </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bilateral and multilateral donor agencies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Notwithstanding these positive initiatives, at the programme level, it is difficult to evaluate the extent to which DFID has indeed mainstreamed disability across its work. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It remains the case that the economic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> case for the inclusion of disability issues within the international development framework needs to be constantly made and reaffirmed. The evidence base for inclusion of disability issues, though growing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> still needs to be strengthened.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A development of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a coherent disability strate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gy by DFID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would be very positive. It would embed a disability component into DFID’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and provide a clear set of priorities. This should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">developed in collaboration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with civil society institutions, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">including disabled peop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le’s organisations. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We strongly recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that this consultation process includes the input from disabled people and their representative organisations in low and middle income countries. DFID’s future disability strategy should embrace the principles and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commitments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">set out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the UNCRPD. It should also reflect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the outcomes of The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Report of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">High Level Panel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of Eminent Persons on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ost-2015 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evelopment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">genda</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the post-2015 development agenda and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the global development framework. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In order to ensure that disability issues are systemically institutionalised within DFID, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recommended that a full-time senior civil servant is appointed in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">department</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, whose primary role is to make sure that d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isability is included in all DFID policy and strategy initiatives including country programmes and DFID-funded projects with civil society institutions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Integration of disability issues within DFID’s sector programmes (for example in health, education, sa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">nitation, livelihoods, and empowerment) and its humanitarian work</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a strong link between disability and multi-dimensional poverty</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It is not lack of funds alone but a lack of inclusion in important areas such as education, health services and soc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ial participation, as well as compounding factors such as gender, age and geographical location, that limit the opportunities for disabled people to overcome poverty. Research from the Leonard Cheshire Disability Inclusive Development Centre has recently t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ermed this the ‘Disability and Development Gap’</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: disabled people who are not included in development efforts fall increasingly further behind non-disabled members of their communities as development efforts increase. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leonard Cheshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">endorses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the twin track approach to disability service provision as outlined in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> issues paper, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Disability, Poverty and Development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (2000). We therefore recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that DFID finances specifically targeted disability programmes as well as enabling disabled people and their families to access mainstream public services and development initiatives (including water and sanitation, public health, education and social pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tection).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The evaluation strategy developed for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID’s Girls’ Education Challenge (GEC) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gives a unique opportunity to generate strong evidence of what works and what does not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leonard Cheshire Disability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">welcomes the effort made by GEC to strengthen the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">monitoring and evaluation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> capacity of implementing agencies and to fund research initiatives. However there needs to be the right balance between the effort invested in generating the evidence and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">direct response to the needs of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabled people.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs to develop </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">robust moni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">toring and evaluation framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at international and country level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This is in relevant in two </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">areas: first, with regard to DFID’s five-year country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> operational plans; and second</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with regard to DFID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programmes through civil </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">society institutions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should clearly measure and evaluate the specific impact(s) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID’s disability-specific and mainstream initiatives have on disabled people. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">minimum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">data </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disaggregated by age, sex, categor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y of impairment, and where possible, ethnicity, and geographical location (urban/rural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">divide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also important that DFID actively engages and provides financial support for the empowerment of disabled people’s organisations in low and middle income </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">countries. Therefore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should fund the institutional development and strengthening of disabled people’s organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n order to make disability-specific and mainstream programmes more inclusive,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> financial resources should be provided to support the design of innovative programmes at country level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> We further encourage DFID to ensure that all key stakeholders receive Disability Awareness training and that disabled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> routinely sit on project</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> advisory board</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The strength of the evidence base on ‘what works’ in development programmes involving disability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Four examples a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re given below that demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> some of the innovative work that Leonard Cheshire Disab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ility has undertaken globally. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is not a comprehensive list but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">instead </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provides some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">examples </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the evidence base on ‘what works’ in development programmes involving disability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cross-Cutti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ng Disability Research Programme</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Cross-Cutting Disability Research Programme</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was a three-year initiative funded by DFID and managed by the Leonard Cheshire Disability and Inclusive Development Centre. The mandate was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to work with other DFID-funded Research Programme C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onsortia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(RPC) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to mainstream a disability component into other i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nternational development research areas. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">esearch was undertaken i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n collaboration with other RPCs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the fields of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">access for persons with disabilities to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">water and sanitation (Zambia and Uganda); maternal and child health (Nepal); mental health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stigma </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and multi-dimensional poverty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(India); and urban agriculture (Kenya). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One of the key lessons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> learned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from this research programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was that disability often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not considered </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mainstream RPCs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It is therefore essential</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">build the capacity of disabled p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople and their representative organisations on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how to undertake and use research in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eir core campaigning activities.</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Leonard Che</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">shire Disability’s Young Voices</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leonard Cheshire D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isability’s Young Voices programme,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supported by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">European Union</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">des clear evidence of the value of making young disabled people the agents of their own destiny within development programmes. Young Voices is a global network of over 1,200 young disabled campaigners from over 20 countries in the global South. Through the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> project, young disabled people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gain the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> skills and confidence they need to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">engage with decision makers to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effectively advocate and campaign to end the extreme poverty, discrimination and exclusion experienced by people with disabilities in lower income co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">untries. The voices of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">young people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with disab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ilities are often marginalised. Through their focused</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> advocacy campaigns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Young Voices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contributed to changing both local and national discourses on disability and participated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at an international level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rough </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the UN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and UNICEF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Initiatives such as this can be a catalyst for building the next generation of the disability movement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Inclusive education</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Through our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inclusive education projects across</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Africa and Asia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leonard Cheshire Disability has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> supported over 10,000 children with disabilities to go to school.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inclusive education work in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Bangladesh, India and Pakistan, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upported by Big Lottery Fund</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was recognised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Best Practices </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Including Persons </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">All Aspects </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">De</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">velopment Efforts’</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> published by UN in April 2011. The project </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supported children with disabilities to access mainstream primary edu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">upported them to continue their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over 3,000 teachers were trained on accommodating children with disab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ilities in their classes. Preparatory classes for children with disabilities were organised prior to enrolment into mainstream schools, and an effective home-based education system was designed for areas where the terrain made it hard for children with hig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h support needs to get to school. The project worked closely with schools to make them accessible; and with government officials to ensure that children with disabilities received any government entitlements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> due to them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">project also undertook advocacy and policy work, including the formation of parents groups and child-to-child clubs for children with and without disabilities to support meaningful inclusion. In total, over 2,700 children were successfully enrolled in thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r local primary schools. The project had a significant impact on changing attitudes towards disabled children’s rights to education; there are now more children with disabilities in local primary schools in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the project locations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Livelihoods</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leonard Che</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shire Disability’s Livelihoods Resource Centres (LRCs) in Asia </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Africa </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(supported by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funders including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Accenture and the European Union</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> respectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have been selected by the Zero Project</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as an example of ‘Innovative Practice’ relating to persons with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabilities and employment. LRCs act as ‘one-stop-shops’ for disabled people seeking employment, providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">skills </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">training, career guidance and links between employees and employers. There are now 22 LRCs in 9 countries across Asia and Africa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We have su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pported over 10,000 adults with disabilities into paid or self-employment, and provided training for nearly 50,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. LRCs are unique in providing the full range of support that disabled people need when seeking employment or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">starting their own enterprise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. L</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CD partner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with mainstream training institutions, ensuring disabled people get recognised qualifications. The training is also tailored to meet the needs of local employment markets, as well as people’s own interests and talents. Training provision in “so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ft skills” (including confidence building, decision making, and critical thinking) also supports the project’s success. In order to support self-employment, the microfinance model used by LRCs includes savings and insurance, known to be an effective povert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y reduction tool.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of disabled beneficiaries in planning, managing and monitoring DFID policy and programmes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It has long been recognised, especially in rural development and international gender studies, that the most sustainable and efficient </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">outcomes of development initiatives occur when participatory approaches to policy and programme design are employed</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Within the international disability and development sector, a good example of this was the negotiation process of the UNCRPD. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dopting a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> participatory approach, if undertaking in a non-tokenistic manner, will incur financial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and human costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – for example provision of sign language interpreters,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> physically accessible venues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, covering transport etc. We recommend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that explicit reference is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">made</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within the DFID disability strategy to the need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to involve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabled people and their allies in the development of DFID-funded disability initiatives. It will also be important to explicitly state what processes and methodology will be employed to ensu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re such engagement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We believe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that both disabled and non-disabled people have a legitimate role to play in relation to policy design, programme implementation and evaluation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DFID to establish a working group, comprised of key individuals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> working in the disability and international development arena, who will provide strateg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ic advice and guidance to DFID on this issue.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The financial costs and benefits of an increased emphasis on disability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The financial and human costs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">continuing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">exclusion of disability in international development are substantial. In 2000, the World Bank estimated that the annual loss to global GDP of people with disabilities not working who were in a position to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> was between $1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.37 trillion and $1,94 trillion</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This figure is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> likely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to have increased substantially since 2000.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the International Labour Organization’s 2009 study en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">titled ‘The Price of Exclusion: The Economic Consequences of Excluding People with Disabilitie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s from the World of Work’</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he tota</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">annual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cost of avoidable unemployment among disabled persons to national economies was estimated to be between 1% and 7%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of GDP</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The UK’s role in ensuring post-2015 development goals consider disability issues</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Millennium Development Goals made no explicit reference to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disability issues. This was a significant omission</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The post-2015</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> development framework must explicitly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">include disability.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This includes not only the final set of goals but systematic inclusion of disability in the monitoring and evaluation mechanisms built into all targets and indicators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that DFID </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a leading, strategic role in ensuring that disability iss</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ues are incorporated into the post-2015 international development framework</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Priority areas should include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.87pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ensuring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">human rights standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are acknowled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UNCRPD</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.87pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Generating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comparative, disaggregated data in relation to disability policy d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evelopment and programming</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.87pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eveloping appropriate tools for monitoring the impact of disability in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disability-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">specific and ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">instream development programmes</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tiziana Oliva</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Director of International</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Leonard Cheshire Disability</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Telephone: 02032420216</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Email: tiziana.oliva@LCDisability.org</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h2><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">Inquiry on Disability and International Development - Written Evidence from Leonard Cheshire Disability to the House of Commons Select Co